Republic of the Philippines
Bangsamoro Autonomous Region in Muslim Mindanao
**BANGSAMORO TRANSITION AUTHORITY**
Cotabato City

Second Parliament
First Regular Session

Parliament Bill No. 42
(Cabinet Bill)

Introduced by:
**THE GOVERNMENT OF THE DAY**

**AN ACT STRENGTHENING IRRIGATION SYSTEMS IN THE BANGSAMORO REGION AND PROVIDING FUNDS THEREFOR, AND FOR OTHER PURPOSES**

Be it enacted by the Bangsamoro Transition Authority in Parliament assembled:

**SECTION 1.** Short Title. – This act shall be known as the “Bangsamoro Irrigation Act of 2022”.

**SECTION 2.** Declaration of Policy. – It is the declared policy of the Bangsamoro Government to advance agriculture as a key development strategy, promote productivity measures, and provide support for small farmers, landholders, and marginal fisher folks. Irrigation is a major component of agricultural modernization in the Bangsamoro Autonomous Region. The prospective expansion of irrigated lands in the BARMM will contribute significantly to the agricultural progress and economic growth of the autonomous region.

It is also a declared policy of the Bangsamoro Government to promote agriculture as ameans to alleviate poverty and food sufficiency in the Bangsamoro regions. To this end, a reliable and efficient system of irrigation shall be established to complement the existing agricultural infrastructure and increase the yield of our agricultural produce.

An integrated approach is vital to the adequate supply of irrigation in both upstream and downstream areas, thus the policy of convergence and cooperation between national and local agencies is recognized as a vital means of strengthening the irrigation system in the Bangsamoro region.

Moreover, it is the declared policy of the State that it is committed through GOCCs, like the NIA, in lowering the cost of production through the provision of free irrigation service, and further relieving the farmers and their irrigators associations from the burden and consequence of unpaid irrigation service fees.

**SECTION 3.** Scope. – This Act shall apply to all areas of irrigable agricultural land in the Bangsamoro Region. Priority shall be given to Small Scale Irrigation Projects (SSIP) and farmers with landholding of eight (8) hectares or below. Institutional arrangement on nationally-funded projects which shall be under the sole authority of the National Irrigation Authority (NIA) shall be defined in this Act.

**SECTION 4.** Creation and Defining the Structure of Irrigation Institutions in the Bangsamoro Region. – There is hereby created Bangsamoro Irrigation Board, herein referred as the ‘Board’, which serves as the policy-making body on irrigation matters in the Bangsamoro region. The Board is supported by the Bangsamoro Irrigation Office, herein referred as the ‘Office’, which will serve as the operational arm of the Board. The Board is attached to the Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries and Agrarian Reform (MAFAR).

**SECTION 5.** Composition of the Bangsamoro Irrigation Board. – The Bangsamoro Irrigation Board shall be composed of the following:

(a) Ministry of Agriculture, Fisheries, and Agrarian Reform (MAFAR), as Chairman of the Board;
(b) Ministry of Environment and Natural Resources (MENRE);
(c) Ministry of Public Works (MPW);
(d) Ministry of Interior and Local Government (MILG);
(e) Representative of the National Irrigation Board;
(f) Representatives of the concerned Local Government Unit and Concerned Provincial/Municipal Agriculture Officer.

The Regional Bangsamoro Irrigation Board shall convene at least once every quarter.

**SECTION 6.** Powers and Functions of the Board. – The Regional Bangsamoro Irrigation Board shall have the following functions:

(a) Define irrigation system framework in the Bangsamoro Region;
(b) Approve irrigation-related policies, plans, programs, and projects to be funded and implemented by the Bangsamoro Government;
(c) Identify and assess areas that are in need of irrigation service, and supervise the development, operation, and maintenance of the irrigation system to be established.
(d) Establish linkages with irrigation agencies, including but not limited to the National Irrigation System led by the NIA, Small Scale Irrigation Projects by the Department of Agriculture and the Watershed Management by the Department of Environment and Natural Resources, projects of Irrigation Associations and other Community Irrigation System;
(e) Ensure support to the irrigators associations in order to improve their productivity;and
(f) Ensure the implementation of Republic Act No. 10969; or the “Free Irrigation Service Act”. To this end, the Regional Bangsamoro Irrigation Board shall keep a registry of all entitled beneficiaries’ farmers and identify challenges in the implementation of this law.

Chunk Complete. Ready for next group of provisions starting at Section 7.

***

**SECTION 7.** Functions and Responsibilities of the Office. – The Bangsamoro Irrigation Office shall have the following functions and responsibilities:

(a) To implement irrigation programs and projects that are funded by the Bangsamoro Government and supported by official development assistance (ODA);
(b) To coordinate with the National Irrigation Administration with regard to the construction and maintenance of nationally-funded irrigation systems and irrigation systems that connect to or from facilities outside the Bangsamoro Autonomous Region;
(c) To assess and inventory all inland waters such as lakes, rivers, river systems, and streams within BARMM territorial jurisdiction in coordination with the Ministry of Environment and Natural Resources (MENRE) as part of the region’s inland water systems for agricultural production purposes;
(d) To coordinate with appropriate agencies of government in the preservation and management of the inland waters within the Bangsamoro Autonomous Region;
(e) To conduct regular monitoring and evaluation of the progress of the implementation of regional irrigation programs and projects, including implementation problems and issues, and recommend solutions for the purpose;
(f) To participate in the planning and policy formulation for the development, utilization, and maintenance of irrigation systems in the Bangsamoro Autonomous Region;
(g) To assess and inventory all existing irrigation systems in the BARMM and their present status and conditions, and make appropriate recommendations for the purpose;
(h) To establish and maintain a database management system for irrigation systems inthe Bangsamoro Autonomous Region;
(i) To represent the Bangsamoro region in all activities pertinent to irrigation development plans and programs;
(j) To lead the formulation of a roadmap to further develop the irrigation systems of the Bangsamoro Autonomous Region;
(k) To Identify existing regional irrigation system resources in need of further funding, repair and maintenance;
(l) Formulate Bangsamoro Agriculture-Irrigation Development Plan from the data gathered and requested from the farmers, irrigation association and the Local Government Units, in coordination with all member agencies;
(m) Establish coordination with Irrigation Associations and provide technical support in order to ensure the full operation of irrigation systems; and
(n) To perform other tasks as directed by the Chief Minister or other competent authority which includes the NIA Administrator.

**SECTION 8.** Organizational Structure of the Office. – The Office shall be headed by an Executive Director I. The Office shall be composed of the following divisions:

(a) Research, Planning, and Policy Division;
(b) Coordination and Operations Division;
(c) Monitoring and Evaluation Division; and
(d) Finance and Administrative Support Division.

**SECTION 9.** Functions and Responsibilities of the Executive Director. – The Executive Director shall have the following functions and responsibilities:

(a) Provide direction and supervision over the full operation of the Bangsamoro Irrigation Office;
(b) Provide policy guidelines and standards for the effective and efficient operation and function of the Office in accordance with its mandate and responsibilities;
(c) Establish a recruitment system guided by civil service rules and regulations in the selection of its prospective staff and employees in the career service;
(d) Ensure that the mandate and functions of the Office and the provisions of this Act are faithfully executed and performed;
(e) Actively participate in the meetings, conferences and other functions of the cabinet; and
(f) Lead the formulation of policy measures as well as development plans and programs for the benefit, protection, and welfare of the beneficiaries of irrigation facilities and infrastructure.

**SECTION 10.** Functions and Responsibilities of the Division. – The technical and administrative divisions shall have the following functions and responsibilities:

1. Research, Planning and Policy Division. – The Research, Planning and Policy Division shall have the following functions and responsibilities:

(a) Develop and maintain a data and information system that will serve as a repository of processed data and statistical information related to water supply and irrigation systems;
(b) Coordinate with local researchers based on statistical data, as required for planning and policy formulation and project development related to water services and irrigation and infrastructure-related matters;
(c) Oversee and conduct studies and research on aspects of regional development concerning agriculture, water resources, flood control, and irrigation development;
(d) Coordinate with concerned offices for comprehensive policy formulation, planning, and investment programming for irrigation-related infrastructure facilities and utilities;
(e) Coordinate the preparation of the socio-economic profile of irrigation project service areas; and
(f) Perform such other functions as may be directed by the Executive Director and other competent authority.

2. Coordination and Operations’ Division. - The Coordination and Operations’ Division shall have the following functions and responsibilities:

(a) Coordinate the implementation of all irrigation development projects in the Bangsamoro region in cooperation with concerned agencies at the national and regional levels;
(b) Coordinate with the implementing agencies relative to the Irrigators’ Association and farmers’ organization issues and concerns in the maintenance and operation of their irrigation systems;
(c) Coordinate with the appropriate national and Bangsamoro Government agencies in the proper management and maintenance of projects related to water supply, drainage control, and irrigation systems;
(d) Review and evaluate area irrigation project proposals and make appropriate actions and recommendations to the appropriate agency;
(e) Provide technical assistance and services to local government units in identifying sources of irrigation water, from inland waters like lakes, rivers, and streams for development;
(f) Implement irrigation programs and projects in the Bangsamoro region that are funded by the Bangsamoro Government; and
(g) Perform such other functions as may be directed by the Executive Director and other competent authority.

3. Monitoring and Evaluation Division. – The Coordination, Monitoring and Evaluation Division shall have the following functions and responsibilities:

(a) Conduct monitoring and evaluation activities related to planning and implementation of irrigation development projects in cooperation with the appropriate agency of the National and Bangsamoro Government;
(b) Monitor and evaluate the progress of privately-owned irrigation project implementation or private systems initiated by individuals or group of farmers;
(c) Submit regular monitoring and evaluation reports to higher authorities pertaining to the actual progress of programs and project implementation; and
(d) Perform other functions as may be directed by the Executive Director and other competent authority.

4. Finance and Administrative Support Division. – The Finance and Administrative Support Division shall have the following functions and responsibilities:

(a) Provide support services relating to personnel, staff development, records management, supplies and equipment, budgeting and accounting, collection, and general clerical and utility services; and
(b) Perform other related functions as may be assigned by the Executive Director and other competent authorities.

Chunk Complete. Ready for next group of provisions starting at Section 11.

***

**SECTION 11.** Local Government Participation. — The Local Government Units shall, together with the National Irrigation Administration and the Municipal Agriculture Officer, submit plans and periodic reports on the status of irrigation in their respective areas.

**SECTION 12.** Coordination and Convergence. - The Ministry of Agriculture and Agrarian Reforms as chair of the Bangsamoro Irrigation Board shall ensure cooperation and convergence between all government agencies and projects affecting the supply of water and irrigation in agricultural lands.

**SECTION 13.** Private participation. —The members of the Bangsamoro Irrigation Board shall recognize the invaluable participation of the private sector for the development of Irrigation services all throughout the Bangsamoro area. To this end, public-private corporations and partnerships shall be actively sought and encouraged.

**SECTION 14.** Appropriations. —The funds necessary to carry out the implementation of this Act shall be charged against the annual appropriations of the Bangsamoro Government without prejudice to the nationally-funded projects.

**SECTION 15.** Implementing Rules and Regulations. - Within sixty (60) days from the promulgation of this Act, the necessary rules and regulations for the proper implementation of its provision shall be formulated.

**SECTION 16.** Separability Clause. – If for any cause, any part of this Act is declared unconstitutional or contrary to the provisions of R.A. 11054, the rest of the provisions shall remain in force and effect.

**SECTION 17.** Repealing Clause. —All laws, decrees, orders, rules and regulations, or any part thereof, which are inconsistent herewith, are hereby repealed or amended accordingly.

**SECTION 18.** Effectivity. – This Act shall take effect after fifteen (15) days following its full publication in a newspaper of general circulation in the Bangsamoro Autonomous Region in Muslim Mindanao.

Approved,

**HON. AHOD BALAWAG EBRAHIM**
Chief Minister

(Sgd.)
**ABDULRAOF A. MACACUA**
Senior Minister
